Hawaii Experiment Station at Poamoho about August to September 1950 , “practically all the ripening tomatoes were infested with melon-fly larvae” (listed as
Dacus cucurbitae
) before a first spray on 2 October. In another field (at the Mid-Pacific Farm of the University of Hawaii at Manoa), tomatoes were beginning to ripen on 18 October 1950 (the day of a first border spray), and “it appeared that practically all ripening fruits were infested.”

